# Fork & upstream PR workflow

**Remotes**: origin = your fork (push here). upstream = canonical repo (no direct push; changes go via PR).

**Tone**: Minimal git commentary. Run required commands; confirm outcome briefly (e.g. "Pushed. PR shows only your change.").

## Single-feature integration branch

When only one feature (e.g. fetchLoanAccountChargeDetails) must go upstream from an integration branch, with no unrelated commits:

1. Reset branch to upstream: `git fetch upstream <branch>`, `git checkout <branch>`, `git reset --hard upstream/<branch>`.
2. Apply only the intended change: edit the affected file(s) or cherry-pick the feature commit. Do not merge a branch that brings in other work.
3. Commit with a single-purpose message.
4. Push to origin: `git push origin <branch> --force-with-lease`. Force is acceptable on your fork's integration branch when producing a clean diff.

## PR into upstream

- **Base**: upstream branch (e.g. khoslalabs:mfi_integration_v3.2.8.3). **Head**: origin branch (e.g. DarpanSolanki:mfi_integration_v3.2.8.3).
- Before merge: verify the PR "Files changed" shows only the intended diff. If not, redo the branch as above.

## Contract

- Do not push directly to upstream. Changes are backward-compatible: additive keys and optional behaviour only; no removal or semantic change of existing fields unless agreed.

## Fork integration branch on upstream (no lost fork-only commits)

Use this when **origin** carries commits that are **not** on **upstream** yet (hotfixes, QA-only merges, portfolio tweaks) but you still want the branch to sit on the **latest upstream production line** (same branch name, e.g. `mfi_integration_v3.2.8.4.1`).

1. Fetch both remotes separately (avoid `git fetch upstream origin` — Git treats the second token as a refspec on `upstream`, not a second remote):  
   `git fetch upstream --prune && git fetch origin --prune`
2. `git checkout <integration_branch>` then `git reset --hard origin/<integration_branch>` so you start from what the fork last published.
3. `git rebase upstream/<integration_branch>` — replays **only** commits that are on origin but not on upstream onto the current upstream tip. Resolve conflicts if any; prefer keeping upstream semantics and re-applying fork deltas.
4. `git push origin <integration_branch> --force-with-lease` — updates the fork without dropping the replayed commits (hashes change; that is expected).

**Downstream feature branches** (e.g. `…_payment_reinitiation` created from upstream-only before this sync): after step 4, either `git reset --hard origin/<integration_branch>` (if they have no unique commits yet) or `git rebase origin/<integration_branch>` so they inherit **upstream + fork-only** work in one line.

Repeat whenever upstream advances on that integration branch so PRs and local work stay aligned with production and fork-only code is not stranded on an old base.

